                  <decoDesc>
                    <summary>(added in the late-twentieth century by the “shiny paint artist”)</summary>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d1"><locus target="#25v" facs="030">Fol. 25v</locus><desc><ref type="authFile" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/AT1082Angel">Angel</ref> with caption (l. to r.) <q>“Wälätä Hǝywät,” and “Diyablos.” </q></desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d2"><locus target="#26r" facs="030">Fol. 26r</locus><desc>left: Two evil entities rise from a central box. From the right entity a serpent descends; from the left entity the head of a bird. with caption upper left,<q> Yabäla, “Feeding” and upper right, Nǝguś, “King.”</q></desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d3"><locus target="#26r" facs="030">Fol. 26r</locus><desc>right: A man works with hammer and large nail with caption <q>Wise man” (with skillful hands)</q></desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d4"><locus target="#87r" facs="091">Fol. 87r</locus><desc>folio prepared with bed of paint over text, but the miniature was never painted</desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d5"><locus target="#91r" facs="095">Fol. 91r</locus><desc>Man holding large ornate <term key="cross" ana="#cross"/>; man holding umbrella, figure seated; man standing with arms folded across chest and holding gun and <term key="sword" ana="#sword"/> with caption (l. to r.) <q>“Jesus’ cross,”</q></desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="frame" xml:id="d6">
                      Decorative designs:
                      <locus target="#1r #7r #13v #21r #30r #42v #50v #61r #68v #73v #86r #97r #100r #105v #111v #123r #130r" facs="005 012 018 025 034 047 055 065 073 078 090 101 104 110 116 127 134">folss. 1r, 7r, 13v, 21r, 30r, 42v, 50v, 61r, 68v, 73v, 86r, 97r, 100r, 105v, 111v, 123r, 130r, </locus> (harägs);
                      <locus target="#36v #42r #50v #61r #68v #73v #97r #105v #123r" facs="041 046 055 065 073 078 101 110 127">36v, 42r, 50v, 61r, 68v, 73v, 97r, 105v, 123r</locus>, (a line of alternating red and black dots)
                    </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                    <list>
                      <item xml:id="a1">
                    <desc type="Asmat">
                      <locus target="#iir(ecto) #iiv(erso) #iiir(ecto) #iiiv(erso)" facs="002 003 004">Fols. iir(ecto), iiv(erso), iiir(ecto), iiiv(erso)</locus>
                      Asmat prayer for protection in pregnancy and child birth,
                      containing one stanza from the Image of Rufa’el, <foreign xml:lang="gez">መልክአ፡ ሩፋኤል፡</foreign>, very carefully written
                      Incipit for Asmat prayer:
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">በስመ፡ አብ፡ <gap reason="omitted"/> ጸሎት፡ በእንተ፡ ጽቡስት፡ (sic) እለ፡ ይወልዳ፡</foreign>
                      Stanza from Image of Rufael (<locus target="#iii(verso)" facs="004">iii(verso)</locus>. This stanza is often recited during childbirth
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">
                      ሰላም፡ ለልሳንከ፡ ዘኢያጸርዕ፡ ስብሐታተ፡<lb/>
                      ለቃልከ፡ ሰላም፡ ወለእስትንፋስከ፡ ሕይወተ፡<lb/>
                      ሩፋኤል፡ ትጉኅ፡ እንተ፡ ተዓቅብ፡ ነፍሳተ፡<lb/>
                      ለሰብእ፡ ወለእንስሳ፡ ፈታሔ፡ ማኅፀኖሙ፡ አንተ፡<lb/>
                      ወጽላሎትከ፡ ያነሥእ፡ ምውተ፡
                      </foreign>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a2">
                    <desc type="Asmat">
                      <locus target="#ivr(ecto)" facs="004"> f. ivr(ecto), column 1</locus>: Asmat prayers to Saints Michael and Gabriel.
                        <foreign xml:lang="gez">በስመ፡ አብ፡ ወወልድ፡<gap reason="omitted"/> ኤኮስ፡ አስኬ፡ ኤዎስ፡ ኤዎስ፡  ኤንከምካም፡<gap reason="omitted"/></foreign>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a3">
                    <desc>
                      <locus target="#ivr(ecto)" facs="004"> f. ivr(ecto), column 2</locus>: Asmat prayers for the revelation of wisdom and understanding
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">በስመ፡ አብ፡<gap reason="omitted"/> አስማተ፡ ኃይል፡ ዘወጽአ፡፡እማፉሁ፡ ለእግዚአብሔር፡</foreign>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a4">
                    <desc type="OwnershipNote">
                      <locus target="#ir(ecto)" facs="001">Fol. ir(ecto)</locus> Säfiw Amarä
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a5">
                    <desc>
                      <locus target="#iv(erso)" facs="002">Fol. iv(erso)</locus> List of names
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a6">
                    <desc type="DonationNote">
                      <locus target="#ivv(erso)" facs="005">Fol. ivv(erso)</locus>:
                      Notes on the gift of the manuscript, in blue ink, in a later hand:
                      “This Psalter belongs to Fit’awrari Sǝyum Wälälu and Wäyzäro Laqäč…who gave it to Mämhǝr Gäbrä Mädḫǝn… to show the way for the kingdom of heaven. Yäkatit 19, 19?? (illegible)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e1">
                    <desc>
                      <locus target="#144r #144v" facs="148 149">Fols. 144r, 144v</locus>: blank
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a7">
                    <desc>
                      <locus target="#56r" facs="060">Fol. 56r</locus>:
                      A text,
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">በዝየ፡ መንፈቀ፡ ዳዊት፡ ዝኒ፡ መርሖሙ፡ </foreign>“Here is half of the Psalter, that is, [the word] <foreign xml:lang="gez">መርሖሙ፡</foreign>,” surrounded in an ornate box, marks the midpoint of the psalms
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e2">
                    <desc>
                      words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#28v #36r #47v #49v #51v" facs="033 040 052 054 056">folss. 28v, 36r, 47v, 49v, 51v, </locus> etc.);
                      and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#1v #5v #32v #35v #39r" facs="006 010 037 040 043">1v, 5v, 32v, 35v, 39r, </locus> etc.);
                      text has been removed (e.g. <locus target="#6r #11v #16v #66v #78v" facs="010 016 021 071 083">6r, 11v, 16v, 66v, 78v</locus>)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e3">
                    <desc>
                      The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line.
                      Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an
                      appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate
                      script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe
                      reduces the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the
                      next line (throughout)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    </list>
                  </additions>
